 WMI (Windows Management Instrumentation)
WMI is a Windows management technology used to manage and monitor computers. It provides information about hardware, software, processes, and service performance.
 Implementation: It is the Microsoft implementation of WBEM (WebBased Enterprise Management) and CIM (Common Information Model) from the DMTF (Distributed Management Task Force).
 Purpose:
 Share management info between applications.
 Helps admins monitor and manage systems locally or remotely.
# Uses of WMI
 Hardware and software inventory.
 System configuration.
 Event monitoring.
 Performance monitoring.
 Registry and file system access.
 Automation and scripting.
 Important WMI Basics
 WMI Service Name: Winmgmt
 Runs under: svchost.exe
 Default Startup Type: Automatic
 Depends on: RPC (Remote Procedure Call)
 WMI Provider Host: Wmiprvse.exe
# Key Components
1. WMI Service (Winmgmt): The main management service.
2. WMI Control (wmimgmt.msc): The configuration console.
3. WMI Provider Host (Wmiprvse.exe): Provides system data.
4. WBEMTest: A testing tool for running WMI queries.
 WMI Architecture
1. WMI Consumers: Applications or scripts that request WMI data.
2. WMI Infrastructure: Contains various components:
 WMI Core
 CIM Repository
 COM / DCOM
3. WMI Providers: The middle layer between WMI and hardware/software.
 Three types: SNMP, Registry, and Win32.
 Acts as an intermediary between WMI objects and the WMI service (Winmgmt).
4. WMI Managed Object: The actual resource being managed (e.g., Printer, Hard disk, Process).
 CIM (Common Information Model)
An objectoriented data model managed by DMTF used to represent hardware, software, network resources, etc.
# Levels of CIM
1. Core Classes: All areas of management (represent the managed object).
2. Common Classes: Specific areas of management that apply across platforms.
3. Extended Classes: Technologyspecific additions to common classes.
 WMI Technical Details
# WQL (Windows Query Language)
Used to query WMI information regarding the OS, applications, and system components.
 Example: Select  from Win32_OperatingSystem
 Example: Select  from Win32_BIOS
# Key Terms
 Namespace: A container used to organize WMI classes (e.g., Root\CIMV2, Root\Default).
 WMI Class: A definition of objects; defines properties, data types, and methods.
 COM: A languageindependent system that allows software components to communicate.
 DCOM: An extension of COM that allows communication between remote computers.
 DCOM Security: Access, Launch, Identity, and Connection policy.
 Default Permissions: Remote activation and launch are enabled for admins and disabled for standard users by default.
 Event Tracing and Maintenance
Event Tracing: Tracking and logging events in Windows. Also known as ETW.
# WMI & Event Tracing
Used to record WMI service activity, create WMI logs, and handle event notifications.
 Wevtutil: A tool to enable WMI event tracing and locate WMI events.
# Paths and Commands
 Path to WMI .mof & .dll files: C:\Windows\System32\WBEM
 Path for WMI Repository: C:\Windows\System32\WBEM\Repository
 Compile MOF files: Use the mofcomp command to compile deleted classes/subclasses.
 Register Classes: Use regsvr32 to register classes/subclasses.
 Troubleshooting Tools: WBEMTest, Console, and PowerShell.
# WMI Arbitrator
A component of the WMI service that manages the scheduling and execution of tasks from the WMI client process. It resides in Winmgmt, svchost.exe, etc.
